<DOC><DOCNO> AP890422-0053 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 0941EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-PentagonFraud     04-22 0211</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Pentagon Fraud,220</SECOND><HEAD>Two Given Prison Terms In Probe Of Procurement Corruption</HEAD><DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former Pentagon employee and adismissed executive of Hazeltine Corp., a defense contractor, havebeen given prison terms stemming from the ``Ill Wind''investigation of military procurement corruption.   U.S. District Court Judge Claude M. Hilton on Friday sentencedJack A. Sherman, 52, a one-time civilian Marine Corps contractingsupervisor, to 18 months in prison for taking $43,500 in bribesfrom an unidentified defense consultant in exchange for insideinformation on military contracts.   Hilton also sentenced former Hazeltine vice president Joseph R.Colarusso, 58, to 10 months in prison and fined him $30,000 forimproperly obtaining inside information about a $150 million Navyelectronics contract sought by Hazeltine last year.   Colarusso pleaded guilty in January to conspiracy to defraud thefederal government and to commit wire fraud in connection with hishiring of a defense consultant who obtained the inside data bybribing a Navy engineer.   Also in January, Sherman pleaded guilty to bribery andconspiracy and agreed to pay federal taxes on his unreported bribeincome. He will also pay back the $43,500, which was supplied bythe FBI. The consultant who passed the money to Sherman was workingas an FBI informant.</TEXT></DOC>